Came here for dinner on a Wednesday evening. It was quite busy, but there was a quick table turnaround and we were seated pretty much immediately. I got two fried chicken thighs, a la carte, with a side of macaroni and cheese. The chicken was crazy crispy with a slight spice to it. Excellently seasoned. The macaroni and cheese was great as well, so much creamy, cheese with so much flavor. We got the flight of beignets for dessert - regular, chocolate hazelnut, and apple. A couple of them seemed a bit overcooked, too crunchy, but the chocolate hazelnut was my favorite. Would definitely come back for the chicken and macaroni and cheese.

Great place with great service. I like support local Companies and these guys are worth Trying if you want some soul in your food!

There's a reason there's always a line at Brenda's, but wait it out. It's worth it! Food ordered: 1) Fried Chicken Benedict (5/5): Order any variation of the fried chicken. You will not regret this important decision. The breading on the chicken is wonderfully crunchy, seasoned perfectly, and, what pleasantly surprised me the most, was the fact that the breading does not fall off the chicken meat. In other words, each bite of fried chicken will have a consistent proportion of meat and Cajun seasoned breading. On the side, I chose grits (over potatoes) and they were a bit too buttery for my taste but still good. I just ate around the butter oil border. I love Brenda's! And I do agree with my boyfriend who says that Brenda's Meat & Three is a different experience. I definitely prefer this original Brenda's!

I have been looking forward to trying Brenda's for a long time now. There had to be a reason that there were 10,000 reviews. I decided to go on a Thursday at about 11:30 AM. It was nearly full inside, but there were a couple of tables that were empty so I didn't have to wait at all. This is not your typical brunch place, although you might find some fun twists on the classics. I decided it would be important to try some things that are not the usual eggs and bacon kind of breakfast. I started with the Hangtown Fry, which is an oyster omelette. I had the potatoes on the side, and then the homemade biscuit. Brenda's does not skimp out on these oysters. There were giant oyster chunks in nearly every bite. I've never had oysters in an omelette, but I was surprised that it was pretty good! I thought the eggs in the omelette were a little over done and tough though. The potatoes were unfortunately too salty, but on the bright side, the biscuit was made well. Now the beignets get a lot of talk so I decided to try the beignet flight so I would get one of each kind. The crawfish one is savory with a kick, which is a nice change-up compared to your sweet beignets. My personal favorite was the apple beignet. It tastes like warm apple pie. These were good, but not as amazing as people had made them out to be. If you've had the beignets from Disneyland that are doughy, soft, and fluffy, these were not like that. They are slightly more tougher on the outside and more dense on the inside. On the side I tried their yogurt parfait. Lots of fruit pieces and homemade granola. The granola is delicious! Overall, the food was good, just not so amazing to the point where I would rave about this place and want to return on a constant basis.

Why 5 stars? Because there's a reason this place has 10,000+ reviews. --- --- --- I've had Brenda's bookmarked for more years than I can remember. It must have been somewhere around 2013 when I attempted to visit, only to get kind of lost and not quite be able to find it. This was back when GPS on your phone was slightly less reliable. I just remember standing on a street corner frantically looking for the entrance while attracting the attention of some loiterers who were aggressively trying to engage with me. I eventually just gave up and went elsewhere. But in 2020, technology did not let me down. While I would have loved to enjoy their famous brunch, we stopped in for dinner and I was not disappointed. We started off with some crawfish beignets, which were unique compared to other beignets I've had, but I really loved these. They were almost just like cheesy bread with a little bit of filling in the center. It's hard to imagine coming to Brenda's without experiencing at least one of the many beignets on the menu. We shared a couple of main courses - first up was the pulled pork sandwich. I've eaten a lot of pulled pork in my life, but this was certainly some of the most unique flavoring I've experienced. It's marinated in some sort of sauce I can't quite put my finger on, but I enjoyed it. I really loved the bun, which was some sort of toasted brioche. We also shared the BFC, which was probably the only thing I didn't totally love. It was fine, but pretty run-of-the-mill fried chicken, in my opinion. I did love the accompanying roll and jelly though! We also ordered a side of mac-n-cheese, which was pretty great. And finally, we finished with a coconut cream pie. What made this unique was that it was essentially an Oreo crust. Between that and the coconut flakes, you got a nice crunch in every bite on the top and the bottom of the pie. I think the food overall was somewhere in between 4 and 5 stars, but I'm rounding up due to super friendly service! I'd love to come back and check out brunch here another time. I expected it to be a packed house during dinner, but there were consistently open tables throughout the night on a Thursday. Don't be scared off that you'll have to wait a long time for dinner just because they have 10K+ reviews!

OVER 10k Reviews! This place is a can't miss. I love this place. If you're looking for a place to eat look no further than this soulful treat. Just be prepared to wait. It's usually busy. Also if you're driving, parking will be a bit of an issue. I had to drop my party off first and then circle a few times to find parking a few blocks down. The food here is great. I used to live in East Bay and this was a place I booked marked but never had a chance to go. But on a random trip with friends, I made it a point to come here and come here we did! To start we got the plain beignets. They were a close match to the beignets I tasted at Cafe de Monde in New Orleans so we tried the flight of beignets which had the: plain, Granny Smith, chocolate and crawfish. All were good but I really enjoyed the crawfish beignet. I enjoyed the savory taste. They were big enough to enjoy by itself so if you're not too hungry one beignet is perfect w a cup of coffee. For the entree, we got the Hangtown Fry, Eggs Benedict and Shrimp Grits. (We were hungry) My favorite out of the three was the Shrimp Grits. It was a creamy, rich bowl with nice size shrimps. The cheesy mixture of grits and pieces of bacon was a hearty start. I never was into grits but over the years I really grown to love it. I think it was the movie "My Cousin Vinny" that peaked my interest into trying grits and ever since if I see it on the menu at Southern Restaurants I usually order it. Overall, If you're a local or just visiting, this place should be around the top 5 restaurants to try especially for breakfast! Don't take it from me, take it from the over thousand reviews that rave about this place. Its a MUST stop.

Came in for dinner on a Thursday evening, and was seated right away, but that's probably because it was just me (that's how it's done). Had the seasonal brew pecan ale, the crawfish beignet, and the catfish de allemands. Service was excellent: helpful, available, and on top of it! Food came out within five to ten minutes. The catfish de allemands was amazing! Moist fish fillet with a slightly crispy exterior over a bed of rice pilaf topped with a crawfish etoufee. Seafood craving satisfied. Would definitely order again! Even though I was pretty full, I just had to try their sweet beignet flight, which includes an apple, a chocolate, and a classic beignet. My favorite was actually the apple beignet, which reminded me of the apple pie from McDonald's (don't be hatin'), but with powdered sugar. All the beignets were tasty, but were a tad on the dense side. Overall, great food, service, and ambiance. If I'm ever in SF and craving soul food, will have to stop by again, but maybe with a group, so I can try more of their food!

On a whim my closest of friends decided to brunch and I looked no further than Brenda's as they close later whereas most brunch eateries end their service at 2 or 2:30PM. Upon arrival, it was roughly 2PM, there was a short wait of about 15 minutes before a table for 3 opened up. Service is fabulous as each of the staff are attentive and genuinely willing to assist. You can never go wrong with any of the food choices on their menu. - Get their beignets, they're all Delicious. Coming here on a Thursday around 5:30pm, we were able to get seated right away with no wait. After reading the reviews there were a few items that caught my eye. The Brenda's Fried Chicken, crawfish beignets, pulled pork sandwich, mac and cheese and the low-key star of the night, the coconut cream pie. Crawfish beignets - one word, delicious. Savory treats have a soft spot in my heart. Biting into them, you have some big pieces of crawfish meat, blended with a creamy cajun sauce, crispy crust, all worked really well. (I'd prefer these over the dessert version, any day) Pulled pork sandwich - This had a ton of flavor! Most pulled pork sandwiches tend to be dry, but not at Brendas. The slaw and slightly toasted bread give all the mouth textures you would want from a sandwich. If you like pulled pork, this is worth trying. Brenda's fried chicken - this was my least favorite of all the things I've ate. I've ordered it twice, and have been underwhelmed each time. No real distinct or memorable flavors can be found here. 3pcs come in a meal along with a side of collard greens and biscuit. You got one big piece of chicken breast, and the other pieces are small in comparison. The meat hasn't been juicy, and had me reaching for some hot sauce to add some kick to it. Definitely a pass for me next time around. Mac and cheese - if you like creamy, bechamel type mac n cheese, grab an order of this. Mac n cheese lovers can rejoice because this dish hits. Coconut cream pie - I don't like sweets, but I love oreos. The oreo crust combined with the coconut cream was heavenly. One piece is big enough to share for two people, and not overly sweet. Worth getting if you have room left for dessert. Overall, it's good food and great service. The staff was quick and attentive which made for a pleasant experience. Maybe not a place I'd go out of my way for, but definitely i'd return to if somebody wanted to go.

    I have been looking forward to trying Brenda's for a long time now. There had to be a reason that there were 10,000 reviews. I decided to go on a Thursday at about 11:30 AM. It was nearly full inside, but there were a couple of tables that were empty so I didn't have to wait at all.

    This is not your typical brunch place, although you might find some fun twists on the classics. I decided it would be important to try some things that are not the usual eggs and bacon kind of breakfast. I started with the Hangtown Fry, which is an oyster omelette. I had the potatoes on the side, and then the homemade biscuit. Brenda's does not skimp out on these oysters. There were giant oyster chunks in nearly every bite. I've never had oysters in an omelette, but I was surprised that it was pretty good! I thought the eggs in the omelette were a little over done and tough though. The potatoes were unfortunately too salty, but on the bright side, the biscuit was made well.

    Now the beignets get a lot of talk so I decided to try the beignet flight so I would get one of each kind. The crawfish one is savory with a kick, which is a nice change-up compared to your sweet beignets. My personal favorite was the apple beignet. It tastes like warm apple pie. These were good, but not as amazing as people had made them out to be. If you've had the beignets from Disneyland that are doughy, soft, and fluffy, these were not like that. They are slightly more tougher on the outside and more dense on the inside.

    On the side I tried their yogurt parfait. Lots of fruit pieces and homemade granola. The granola is delicious!

    Overall, the food was good, just not so amazing to the point where I would rave about this place and want to return on a constant basis.

    I've had Brenda's bookmarked for more years than I can remember. It must have been somewhere around 2013 when I attempted to visit, only to get kind of lost and not quite be able to find it. This was back when GPS on your phone was slightly less reliable. I just remember standing on a street corner frantically looking for the entrance while attracting the attention of some loiterers who were aggressively trying to engage with me. I eventually just gave up and went elsewhere. But in 2020, technology did not let me down.

    While I would have loved to enjoy their famous brunch, we stopped in for dinner and I was not disappointed. We started off with some crawfish beignets, which were unique compared to other beignets I've had, but I really loved these. They were almost just like cheesy bread with a little bit of filling in the center. It's hard to imagine coming to Brenda's without experiencing at least one of the many beignets on the menu.

    We shared a couple of main courses - first up was the pulled pork sandwich. I've eaten a lot of pulled pork in my life, but this was certainly some of the most unique flavoring I've experienced. It's marinated in some sort of sauce I can't quite put my finger on, but I enjoyed it. I really loved the bun, which was some sort of toasted brioche.

    We also shared the BFC, which was probably the only thing I didn't totally love. It was fine, but pretty run-of-the-mill fried chicken, in my opinion. I did love the accompanying roll and jelly though!

    We also ordered a side of mac-n-cheese, which was pretty great.

    And finally, we finished with a coconut cream pie. What made this unique was that it was essentially an Oreo crust. Between that and the coconut flakes, you got a nice crunch in every bite on the top and the bottom of the pie.

    I think the food overall was somewhere in between 4 and 5 stars, but I'm rounding up due to super friendly service!

    I'd love to come back and check out brunch here another time. I expected it to be a packed house during dinner, but there were consistently open tables throughout the night on a Thursday. Don't be scared off that you'll have to wait a long time for dinner just because they have 10K+ reviews!

    OVER 10k Reviews! This place is a can't miss. I love this place. If you're looking for a place to eat look no further than this soulful treat. Just be prepared to wait. It's usually busy.     The food here is great. I used to live in East Bay and this was a place I booked marked but never had a chance to go. But on a random trip with friends, I made it a point to come here and come here we did!

    To start we got the plain beignets. They were a close match to the beignets I tasted at Cafe de Monde in New Orleans so we tried the flight of beignets which had the: plain, Granny Smith, chocolate and crawfish. All were good but I really enjoyed the crawfish beignet. I enjoyed the savory taste. They were big enough to enjoy by itself so if you're not too hungry one beignet is perfect w a cup of coffee.

    For the entree, we got the Hangtown Fry, Eggs Benedict and Shrimp Grits. (We were hungry) My favorite out of the three was the Shrimp Grits. It was a creamy, rich bowl with nice size shrimps. The cheesy mixture of grits and pieces of bacon was a hearty start. I never was into grits but over the years I really grown to love it. I think it was the movie "My Cousin Vinny" that peaked my interest into trying grits and ever since if I see it on the menu at Southern Restaurants I usually order it.

    Overall, If you're a local or just visiting, this place should be around the top 5 restaurants to try especially for breakfast! Don't take it from me, take it from the over thousand reviews that rave about this place. Its a MUST stop.

    Having been to Brenda's several times, I am not sure why I have yet to give them a proper review. Well, here it is now.

    This was on Valentines Day, a friday 02/14/2020. On a whim my closest of friends decided to brunch and I looked no further than Brenda's as they close later whereas most brunch eateries end their service at 2 or 2:30PM. Upon arrival, it was roughly 2PM, there was a short wait of about 15 minutes before a table for 3 opened up.

    Service is fabulous as each of the staff are attentive and genuinely willing to assist. You can never go wrong with any of the food choices on their menu.

    - Get their beignets, they're all Delicious. Savory and sweet options are available and you can get all of the flavors in a flight (original, crawfish, and granny smith apple).
    - Try their mimosa, their guava was very refreshing.
    - Their egg benedicts are still as good as I remember from my last visit with the poached eggs dripping in orange lava, yes I said orange lava.
    - Shrimp Po'Boys are also delicious, my friend devoured hers almost immediately. However, she did mention that the shrimp may have been over crispened.
    - Their english muffins are tender and fluffy at the same time, just add some butter and jam and it'll be perfection.

    This is an popular San Francisco brunch institution not to be missed.

    1/24/2020

    Coming here on a Thursday around 5:30pm, we were able to get seated right away with no wait.

    After reading the reviews there were a few items that caught my eye. The Brenda's Fried Chicken, crawfish beignets, pulled pork sandwich, mac and cheese and the low-key star of the night, the coconut cream pie.

    Crawfish beignets - one word, delicious. Savory treats have a soft spot in my heart. Biting into them, you have some big pieces of crawfish meat, blended with a creamy cajun sauce, crispy crust, all worked really well. (I'd prefer these over the dessert version, any day)

    Pulled pork sandwich -  This had a ton of flavor! Most pulled pork sandwiches tend to be dry, but not at Brendas. The slaw and slightly toasted bread give all the mouth textures you would want from a sandwich. If you like pulled pork, this is worth trying.

    Brenda's fried chicken - this was my least favorite of all the things I've ate. I've ordered it twice, and have been underwhelmed each time. No real distinct or memorable flavors can be found here. 3pcs come in a meal along with a side of collard greens and biscuit. You got one big piece of chicken breast, and the other pieces are small in comparison. The meat hasn't been juicy, and had me reaching for some hot sauce to add some kick to it. Definitely a pass for me next time around.

    Mac and cheese - if you like creamy, bechamel type mac n cheese, grab an order of this. Mac n cheese lovers can rejoice because this dish hits.

    Coconut cream pie - I don't like sweets, but I love oreos. The oreo crust combined with the coconut cream was heavenly. One piece is big enough to share for two people, and not overly sweet. Worth getting if you have room left for dessert.

    Overall, it's good food and great service. The staff was quick and attentive which made for a pleasant experience. Maybe not a place I'd  go out of my way for, but definitely i'd return to if somebody wanted to go.
